## Migration Strategy (Clean Architecture Layout)

We will use the **copy-first migration strategy** to build the domain entities and ports before replacing the legacy dependencies:

```text
backend/src/modules/worker/
├── domain/
│   └── entities/Worker.js
├── application/
│   ├── ports/
│   │   ├── WorkerRepositoryPort.js
│   │   └── LocationPort.js
│   └── use-cases/
│       ├── ApproveWorkerKycUseCase.js
│       ├── RejectWorkerKycUseCase.js
│       ├── BlockWorkerUseCase.js
│       ├── UnblockWorkerUseCase.js
│       ├── UpdateWorkerAvailabilityUseCase.js
│       ├── FindNearbyWorkersUseCase.js
│       └── GetWorkerDashboardUseCase.js
└── infrastructure/
    ├── persistence/
    │   ├── schemas/WorkerSchema.js
    │   ├── mappers/WorkerMapper.js
    │   └── repositories/MongoWorkerRepository.js
    └── di/
        └── container.js
```

### Migration Order

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Step 1: Domain Entities & Ports] --> B[Step 2: Mongoose WorkerSchema & Mappers]
    B --> C[Step 3: MongoDB Worker Repository Adapters]
    C --> D[Step 4: Use Cases Implementation]
    D --> E[Step 5: Awilix Dependency Wires]
    E --> F[Step 6: clean WorkerController & Router]
    F --> G[Step 7: Deploy Models & Routes Proxy Wrappers]
    G --> H[Step 8: Automated Test Execution]
```

1.  **Proxy wrappers creation:**
    *   Rewrite `backend/src/models/Worker.js` to proxy database schema mappings to the clean architecture `WorkerSchema.js`.
    *   Rewrite `backend/src/controllers/workerController.js` to resolve use cases from the DI container.
    *   Rewrite `backend/src/routes/worker.js` to dispatch HTTP requests to the DI-wired controllers.

---

## Rollback Strategy
If any issues are discovered:
1.  Revert the proxy wrappers:
    ```bash
    git restore src/models/Worker.js src/controllers/workerController.js src/routes/worker.js
    ```
2.  The legacy files are restored instantly, and clean architecture packages are left inert in the repository.

